r\n	color:purple;\r\n	mso-themecolor:followedhyperlink;\r\n	text-decoration:underline;\r\n	text-underline:single;}\r\n.MsoChpDefault\r\n	{mso-style-type:export-only;\r\n	mso-default-props:yes;\r\n	font-family:Cambria;\r\n	mso-ascii-font-family:Cambria;\r\n	mso-ascii-theme-font:minor-latin;\r\n	mso-fareast-font-family:\"ï¼­ï¼³ æ˜Žæœ\";\r\n	mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-fareast;\r\n	mso-hansi-font-family:Cambria;\r\n	mso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin;\r\n	mso-bidi-font-family:\"Times New Roman\";\r\n	mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-bidi;}\r\n@page WordSection1\r\n	{size:8.5in 11.0in;\r\n	margin:1.0in 1.25in 1.0in 1.25in;\r\n	mso-header-margin:.5in;\r\n	mso-footer-margin:.5in;\r\n	mso-paper-source:0;}\r\ndiv.WordSection1\r\n	{page:WordSection1;}\r\n--></style><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"mso-fareast-font-family:\" times=\"\" new=\"\" roman\";=\"\" mso-bidi-font-family:\"times=\"\" roman\"\"=\"\">Surf Apparel, Sunglasses, and Lifestyle\r\nGoods</span>\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><br></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><br></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','555-555-5555','dave@wastedsun.com','http://WastedSun.com','','',18.331061,-64.794378,'2015-03-02 16:33:32',18,3,0,'2016-05-23 20:09:53'),(621,15,'Tamarind Tree Trail','<font size=\"4\">The Tamarind Tree Spur Trail<font color=\"#FF0066\"><b> ====== </b></font>runs\r\n between the\r\nNorth Shore Road (Route 20) and the Caneel Hill Trail at the low point \r\nof the saddle between Caneel and Margaret Hills. It was originally by \r\nworkers from the\r\nPastory area of St. John taking a more direct route to their jobs during\r\n the\r\nconstruction of the present day resort at Caneel Bay. The large \r\nshade-giving\r\ntamarind tree at the upper trailhead was a popular resting and meeting \r\nplace.\r\n\r\n</font>','','','https://','','',18.338469,-64.785508,'2015-05-05 11:59:50',21,38,5,'2015-07-01 21:01:42'),(622,15,'Cabritte Horn Trail','<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><font size=\"4\"><b style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\">Cabritte Horn Spur\r\nTrail</b> â€“ <b><font color=\"#9900FF\">(======)</font></b> off the Tektite Trail leads out to a beautiful point\r\nwith the crashing surf below. Again it is Park approved but not maintained by\r\nthem. (Trail Bandit highly recommended ***)</font></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><font size=\"4\"><br></font></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><font size=\"4\"><b style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\">Cabritte Horn Point\r\nSpur</b></font></p><font size=\"4\">\r\n\r\n</font><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><font size=\"4\">The Cabritte Horn Point Spur, the first fork to the left on\r\nthe Tektite Trail, descends through a grassy area to Cabritte Horn Point from\r\nwhere you can enjoy spectacular views of the southeast coast of St. John and on\r\nclear days all the way to St. Croix to the south. Here, the brisk trade winds\r\ncarry the smells of maran and frangipani. Look for barrel cactus with their\r\nedible fruits and wild orchids, which can be found growing in the grass, on\r\nrocks, on cactus branches and in trees.</font></p><font size=\"4\">\r\n\r\n</font><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><font size=\"4\">&nbsp;</font></p><font size=\"4\">\r\n\r\n</font><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><font size=\"4\">Cabritte Horn Point is also an excellent place to observe\r\nsea birds - pelicans, frigate birds gulls and boobies.</font></p><font size=\"4\">\r\n\r\n</font><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><font size=\"4\">&nbsp;</font></p><font size=\"4\">\r\n\r\n</font><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><font size=\"4\">The trail leads to a deep gorge with sheer rock walls\r\ndescending to the sea, so narrow you could easily jump over it. (You don\'t have\r\nto - the trail leads around it.)</font></p>','','','https://','','',18.309069,-64.721442,'2015-05-06 06:49:46',9,39,32,'2015-07-01 21:01:42'),(624,16,'Camelberg Road','\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto\"><font size=\"4\"><b style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"font-family: Times;\">Camelberg Road</span></b><span style=\"font-family: Times;\">\r\nâ€“ Goes through beautiful forest at the top and leads down past ruins to the\r\nLâ€™Esperance Trail. The bottom below the ruins needs work, but it connects to\r\nMollendal and number 9 somehow. (Trail Bandit recommended *)</span></font></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto\"><font size=\"4\"><span style=\"font-family: Times;\"><br></span></font></p><font size=\"4\">\r\n\r\n</font><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto\"><font size=\"4\"><b><span style=\"font-family: Times;\">Camelberg\r\nTrail, St. John US Virgin Islands</span></b><span style=\"font-family: Times;\"></span></font></p><font size=\"4\">\r\n\r\n</font><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto\"><font size=\"4\"><span style=\"font-family: Times;\">Some\r\nintrepid St. John explorers turned me on to this not so well known hike, which\r\nfollows an old Danish Road below Camelberg Mountain, as shown on Peter Oxholmâ€™s\r\nmap of St. John, published some 200 years ago.</span></font></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto\"><font size=\"4\"><span style=\"font-family: Times;\"><br></span></font></p><font size=\"4\">\r\n\r\n</font><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto\"><font size=\"4\"><span style=\"font-family: Times;\">The\r\nold Danish Road is apparent, but overgrown, the trail over the road is rough,\r\nmaintained apparently by the few hikers that use it. Although the trail is\r\nfairly obvious and is marked in placed by ribbons, I used a GPS and a good map\r\nto reassure me of my location. <br></span></font></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto\"><font size=\"4\"><span style=\"font-family: Times;\"><br></span></font></p><font size=\"4\">\r\n\r\n</font><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto\"><font size=\"4\"><span style=\"font-family: Times;\">At\r\nfirst you will be following a mountain ridge, on a relatively flat forest trail\r\nshaded mostly by native dry forest trees. In this area youâ€™ll pass by stands of\r\nsmooth shiny barked, guavaberry, aromatic pepper cinnamon and bay rum trees and\r\nbeautiful rock formations, decorated by algaes and colonized by anthuriums and\r\nbromiliads.</span></font></p><font size=\"4\">\r\n\r\n</font><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto\"><font size=\"4\"><span style=\"font-family: Times;\">As\r\nyou descend towards the Lâ€™Esperance Road, more sun penetrates the canopy and\r\nyouâ€™ll start seeing tyre palm stands and patches of bromiliads growing closely\r\ntogether.</span></font></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto\"><font size=\"4\"><span style=\"font-family: Times;\"><br></span></font></p><font size=\"4\">\r\n\r\n</font><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto\"><font size=\"4\"><span style=\"font-family: Times;\">The\r\nfollowing is a description given to me by a previous explorer:</span></font></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto\"><font size=\"4\"><span style=\"font-family: Times;\"><br></span></font></p><font size=\"4\">\r\n\r\n</font><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto\"><font size=\"4\"><span style=\"font-family: Times;\">â€œThe\r\nCamelberg Trail runs between Centerline Road and the Lâ€™Esperance Road,\r\nbeginning just east of the BVI overlook on Centerline. There is parking on the\r\nsouth side of the road about 200 feet east of the overlook. Walk back toward\r\nthe overlook, and when the bank in your left is about three feet high above the\r\nroad, head into the woods. It is easy to see as others have gone before you.\r\nThe route is whacked out, but not cleared for a trail.</span></font></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto\"><font size=\"4\"><span style=\"font-family: Times;\"><br></span></font></p><font size=\"4\">\r\n\r\n</font><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto\"><font size=\"4\"><span style=\"font-family: Times;\">This\r\nold road is superb all the way out past Camelberg and you should have no\r\ntrouble following it. As you head down toward Fish Bay, the trail is less\r\nobvious, but well hacked out. You should see tapes in the trees.</span></font></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto\"><font size=\"4\"><span style=\"font-family: Times;\"><br></span></font></p><font size=\"4\">\r\n\r\n</font><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto\"><font size=\"4\"><span style=\"font-family: Times;\">As\r\nyou approach the Lâ€™Esperance Road the trail forks near some old ruins that\r\narenâ€™t much, but they are there. There are also many orchids here too. After\r\nthe ruin, the track bears right and works itâ€™s way down toward the gut and down\r\nto the Lâ€™Esperance Road. Ok, there arenâ€™t any great views, but the part of the\r\ntrail before you head down the hill runs through a beautiful forest. If you are\r\ninterested, there is an old stone dam in the gut and a road heading to the\r\nsoutheast from the dam. This road is hacked out part way but there is a 100\r\nfoot section that isnâ€™t.</span></font></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto\"><font size=\"4\"><span style=\"font-family: Times;\"><br></span></font></p><font size=\"4\">\r\n\r\n</font><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto\"><font size=\"4\"><span style=\"font-family: Times;\">Ah,\r\njust when you thought you were done: turn left and hike toward Reef Bay on the\r\nLâ€™Esperance Road. After you pass the gut that runs down to Fish Bay, and are\r\nheading up hill toward Reef Bay, turn left on the old road that heads north.\r\nFollow this road and diagonally up to the saddle. From the saddle, stay to the\r\nleft side of the valley and you will find a track that takes you along the\r\nridge, then turns left and down to the gut. Cross the gut and walk along to the\r\nnext gut, and turn left and up the second gut. Keep looking to your left, and\r\nyou will see the stonework on the side of a road that heads up and back toward\r\nCamelberg. It is back from the gut a bit so look closely. Follow this road\r\nsteeply up the hill. After a bit, the road runs out, (probably it switchbacks\r\nup someplace). Just make your way up and left to the top of the ridge. There\r\nare various tapes in the trees from previous explorations. Once on the ridge,\r\nyou should be able to follow the track of previous travelers, all the way back\r\nthe Camelberg Trail. Turn right and walk back to your parked car.â€</span></font></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','','','https://','','',18.340753,-64.753025,'2015-05-12 11:04:05',6,36,8,'2015-07-01 21:01:42'),(625,16,'Mollendal - Camelberg Road','<font size=\"4\">This track starts, as an old road in Mollendal, becomes a\r\ntrail of sorts, goes over a ridge and down to a gut. Cross this first gut and\r\nfo;;ow along level to the second gut. Go upstream for a few hundred feet,\r\nstaying in the woods on the left side of the gut and look for a big Danish road\r\nheading steeply up. The big road dies but head up to the top of the ridge and\r\nfollow it back to the Camelberg Road.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</font>','','','https://','','',18.338186,-64.748631,'2015-05-12 11:07:30',10,37,10,'2015-07-01 21:01:42'),(626,16,'*Maria Hope Trail','\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><font size=\"4\">This is the southern part of the Maria Hope Trail. It is a\r\nbeautiful old Danish road that leads past the Hope and Paquereau estate ruins\r\nand down to join the Reef Bay Trail. Below the Hope ruins, the trail needs\r\nbetter clearing so do your part. There are several spur trails along the way.\r\n(Trail Bandit recommended *)</font></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><font size=\"4\"><br></font></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><font size=\"4\">Maria Hope Trail From Centerline Road South to the Reef Bay\r\nTrail</font></p><font size=\"4\">\r\n\r\n</font><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><font size=\"4\">From Centerline Road, the Maria Hope Trail follows the old\r\nDanish road through dry forest and leads back to the Reef Bay Trail just below\r\nthe Josie Gut Estate.</font></p><font size=\"4\">\r\n\r\n</font><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><font size=\"4\">&nbsp;</font></p><font size=\"4\">\r\n\r\n</font><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><font size=\"4\">Because of the enormous amount of fill used to create\r\nCenterline Road, access to the southern half of the Maria Hope Trail is\r\nextremely difficult at this original juncture. However, a spur trail, cut by a\r\nlocal hiking society, found at the entrance to the Bordeaux Mountain Road just\r\neast of the mailboxes provides a difficult, although passable, access to the\r\nMaria Hope Trail. This is not an official Park trail, it is only semi-improved\r\nand is not regularly maintained. Be extremely careful. The trail is very steep\r\nand slippery.</font></p><font size=\"4\">\r\n\r\n</font><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><font size=\"4\">&nbsp;</font></p><font size=\"4\">\r\n\r\n</font><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><font size=\"4\">The southern section of the Maria Hope Trail lies at the end\r\nof this spur. It is passable, but with some difficulty, especially toward the\r\nbottom of the trail. Turn left. To the right, the trail ends just below\r\nCenterline Road. Proceeding to the left, the trail leads to two spur trails.\r\nThe first spur goes to the Paquerau Ruins and the second to the more extensive\r\nEstate Hope ruins, which include the remains of the greathouse, the horsemill,\r\na cistern and an animal watering trough. Continuing south, the trail leads to\r\nthe Reef Bay Trail just below the Josie Gut Ruins.</font></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','','','https://','','',18.344544,-64.740919,'2015-05-12 11:12:12',19,38,14,'2015-07-01 21:01:42'),(637,13,'Mare Blu','\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<style>\r\n<!--\r\n /* Font Definitions */\r\n@font-face\r\n	{font-family:\"ï¼­ï¼³ æ˜Žæœ\";\r\n	mso-font-charset:78;\r\n	mso-generic-font-family:auto;\r\n	mso-font-pitch:variable;\r\n	mso-font-signature:-536870145 1791491579 18 0 131231 0;}\r\n@font-face\r\n	{font-family:\"Cambria Math\";\r\n	panose-1:2 4 5 3 5 4 6 3 2 4;\r\n	mso-font-charset:0;\r\n	mso-generic-font-family:auto;\r\n	mso-font-pitch:variable;\r\n	mso-font-signature:-536870145 1107305727 0 0 415 0;}\r\n@font-face\r\n	{font-family:Cambria;\r\n	panose-1:2 4 5 3 5 4 6 3 2 4;\r\n	mso-font-charset:0;\r\n	mso-generic-font-family:auto;\r\n	mso-font-pitch:variable;\r\n	mso-font-signature:-536870145 1073743103 0 0 415 0;}\r\n /* Style Definitions */\r\np.MsoNormal, li.MsoNormal, div.MsoNormal\r\n	{mso-style-unhide:no;\r\n	mso-style-qformat:yes;\r\n	mso-style-parent:\"\";\r\n	margin:0in;\r\n	margin-bottom:.0001pt;\r\n	mso-pagination:widow-orphan;\r\n	font-size:12.0pt;\r\n	font-family:Cambria;\r\n	mso-ascii-font-family:Cambria;\r\n	mso-ascii-theme-font:minor-latin;\r\n	mso-fareast-font-family:\"ï¼­ï¼³ æ˜Žæœ\";\r\n	mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-fareast;\r\n	mso-hansi-font-family:Cambria;\r\n	mso-hansi-theme-font:min